segments.text: Yes, his method of making decisions was remarkable.
And Howard and I always marveled at how good he was.
But once he did that, once he made the decision, he didn't interfere with anything and really needed Howard Vestal.
But this took a while.

They had to get complete confidence in anybody before they did this, and so I didn't realize this at the time, but they had gotten to know me pretty well before they said, go ahead and build anything you want.
Of course, it had to go to them for basic approval, but I would dare say, unlike most universities, Haskell, that
When I renovated Sabeza, that was, when I say I did, when we did, $5 million worth back at a time when money's worth many times what it is today.
I don't believe Mr. Cherry or Howard Vestal ever took a close look at the plan.
They just signed them off, which I appreciate.
And were you given adequate?
opportunity to participate in the planning for the new commons?
Yes, oh yes.
It's always difficult planning facilities, you know that, because you've been there.
But you see what happens is a lot of times your engineering type personnel become so involved they have a tendency to overlook the operator.
That's what happened to us.
That's one of the things that happened to us when the Memorial Student Center, as it exists today, and the Tower Dining Facility, as it exists.
Those decisions as to how they were placed in the building were not made by operators.
That includes Howard and Mr. Cherry.
They were made by people above that who, in the case of the Tower,
saw some facilities in Dallas and said, why can't we have one like this?
And it was, of course, there.
They had a lot of money.
They sold alcoholic beverages.
And people were prosperous by comparison.
And then Memorial Student Center is so difficult in its operation.
It's a very, very difficult thing to make it break even financially.
Let's take that point.
If we were to separate each of the food service operations on campus and look at it with a microscope, which one financially is the most profitable and which is the least?
Well, when I left, always Beza had been most profitable.
And the least would be big cash facilities like Memorial Student Center food services.
And then up at the top of the tower would even be... Oh, that was, yes, that was a loser.
That's what I would assume.
Interesting story about that.
When it was being built, Howard Vestal and I were put on the committee as ad hoc members.
Dr. Holland of the engineers was head of the committee, and he said, well, how are we going to plan this thing?
How are we going to operate?
There was supposed to be a faculty club at that time.
So I said, well, I think you should go out and look to find something that's successful and see what they're doing.
So he and his team went out and spent considerable time, went to many places in the United States, came back, and I said, what did you find?
He said, well, we didn't find anything.
in making profits at one place in North Carolina, but he said it was off campus.
So they decided they didn't want it.
So Howard had told me I would not bother with it.
I got it.
And so we were unhappy with the placement.
In the middle, it's so difficult.
If it's to one side, you could have a group big enough to be possible.
So Howard said, well, he'd at least try to help out.
So he went over and tried to get a change made to have a garbage chute and couldn't even get that.
So that's the way it happened to be mine for quite a while.
And of course now, it's being well run, I believe, and it may be making a good profit.
I hope it is.
But people had money to spend now.
There was very little money and many restrictions during that time.
As you recall, departments couldn't spend any money as a group for, at one period of time, as I remember, for food items.
In those almost 20 years that you served... Well, 22.
Oh yeah, that's right.
I was reversing two numbers.
Did the reporting location for you, did it change?
Well, yes.
After Howard retired, I reported to Eddie Joe Davis, who was a great guy, a wonderful fellow.
Then when he moved out, Chuck Hargill took over his job.
And then when he moved, Don Powell took over his job.
And it was during his tenure that I retired.
Now, with the president's,
the different presidents, how did their style of management differ regarding food service?
Well, I suppose there really wasn't a great deal of difference, except a lot of them didn't have any direct interest in it, because it wasn't exceptional for President Rudder to drop by.
Or to bump into him and he'd say, come over and sit down and let's talk or have a sandwich or something.
Or to call me on the phone.
And the same way with Mr. Cherry.
He might walk in the door.
He often did.
I'd look up and he'd be standing in the door.
And I'd say, well, Mike, can I do anything for you?
He'd all know.
I'd just stop by and see how everything's going.
But that ended pretty well with Cherry and the runners.

departure and of course how then finally those one of the things that i i never did enjoy was that it got so busy the vice presidents didn't have time to visit with you now uh did the other people that reported to vestal and cherry and their successors did you all have weekly meetings in
Well, the element in Howard Vestal's position, not in mine.
Oh, okay.
They had at one time, I think, and discontinued that.
And Howard had a meeting when needed.
He did not have it each week.
The only reason I had it is because of their affairs we had to serve.
And it cut down on a lot of problems.
Do you remember any important decisions relating to food service that went all the way up to the president to get decided?
Yes or no?
No, I can't.
No, I can't.
And you're also then inferring that you can't remember when the president vetoed
positively or negatively, some recommendation that had come up.
No.
In fact, I don't think they ever did a veto or anything.
Okay.
Are there any... Well, as you look back, what were we doing right in those days in your area?
Well, we had some good people.
And we were treated everybody the same, even though it wasn't very good.
And we had some good facilities, good reputation.
And everybody tried hard to do the right thing.
We had a very dedicated group of people all over the campus that just wouldn't stop for anything to get their job done.
Loyalty was absolutely beyond comprehension compared to most places, I think.
And in that sense, it was a good place to be.
And what created that loyalty?
Well, of course, loyalty was more common than it is now.
But I think, for the most part, everybody thought the people above them were fair-minded people.
Nobody was making much money.
And they knew they weren't going to get much when they came into work.
So that wasn't a big hang-up.
So a lot of them really appreciated the fact they had a job.
Because they had come in when jobs were very difficult to find.
And if they left, there's ten people in line for the job.
Who were your key subordinates?
Well, I had Henry Wellens, a retired Army sergeant, and Harold Therrell, who was a retired Army sergeant, and Mr. Ingram, who was a retired Navy petty officer, I believe.
And then later on, we began to have a few more people.
I got some very capable people, like Clinton Burkhart,
a man from up in the east, Mr. Bierman, Dick Kutches over from the Kutcher Club, who was ingenious in serving.
He always said he could touch a plate and make it look better.
And then we got some good bakery personnel in from Notre Dame, hired their head baker.
And we began to get some good people.
We got a little relief on salaries.
Howard Vestal tried, but the biggest relief we ever got was through Eddie Joe Davis.
He really went to bat for some salaries for our people.
We weren't competitive with the commercial world was the problem.
We were competitive if you talk about other universities, but that wasn't our competition.
But we couldn't put on the type of show
For public relations, we needed to by paying policy wages.
In other words, why would they come?
And we had some outstanding people.
R.V.
Ray was one.
You may remember him.
You may know him.
He's an outstanding person.
One of the top people anywhere, I think.
Now, these food service employees normally worked only a 40-hour week?
No, our managers never worked just a 40-hour week.
No, but I'm talking about the regular workers.
Regular workers, yes.
They started on an eight-hour shift.
They worked a 40-hour week.
But now they, quite often, they had to work on weekends.
Yes.
What days did they get off?
Well, it was just, you scheduled them.
It took, each manager had to have his schedule and work this out.
So we had so many capable people this day, pair and serve.
And he did that on a continuous basis.
Of course, we used a lot of students in this operation, too.
When we can get them, that's tough at times.
Let's see.
I see in my notes, give me some examples of some
good Aggie bulls, some student tricks, some goof-offs in the food service facilities.
Well, I'm sure they're more than I know about.
Randy O'Davis always laughs about the fact that we used to have a sign up somewhere that said, eat on your tray, meant to eat in front of you.
He said, it's cartoon and a student sitting on his tray having a meal.
We had one joke going, I think, where I put up a sign that said, take one napkin, save a tree.
And somebody said that another one said, well, take one serving, save your life.
One of the things we did that I must tell you about, we didn't know we were setting a pace with the whole United States at the time.
In 1965, we started a menu board wherein we had students come in, and it took a long time to develop, actually three or four years to its fullest extent, but ask them what they wanted on the menu.
Well, we just didn't think we could do it for a while, but we kept inviting them in and kept working on this, and we would show them the menu.
We had a five-week cycle.
And they would go down the list and tell us what they thought they didn't like or wanted more or less of, and we'd inject it in there.
And then we started adding to that all the new items we could get from anywhere.
And there's a lot of them.
Every week or two, there'll be a new item come up somewhere, and they'd send samples, and we'd cook it and ask them, do you want it served?
And this was one of the finest things we ever did.
But you don't change a menu quickly.
And this took a long time to develop.
And those students become so acquainted with the operation, they become supporters and people that try to help out.
And so we had some fine results of that.
Eliminated some items that
that we shouldn't have, added a lot.
And today, I believe that's copied in some manner or other in almost every university and many of the other institutions in the whole United States.
And to the best of my knowledge and belief, that was the first one of that
exact nature that had ever been developed.
The problem might have been others, but I could never find any evidence.
Do you remember how they reacted, say, at first to pizza or Chinese food or anything like that?
Were there any surprise at that point?
Difficulties in there?
Not much because they had been subjected to this commercially.
It was always a surprise, though.
Advertising has so much to do with the students' likes and dislikes.
We couldn't get them to eat hot biscuits until they started in fast food places.
We had tried to serve them, and they didn't want biscuits.
They wanted toast.
And now they hardly eat toast.
And one of the amusing things about this menu board, and I'd tell them and they'd laugh about it, you know, we had some, I remember one company was advertising spaghetti and meatballs of all things.
So they, this was on a popular show of some kind, so every time we'd meet they'd say, we want some more spaghetti and meatballs.
But one of the things I learned that I didn't know, and it's still a surprise today, the same item is not popular more than about once a week, and some not even then.
Well, we finally got so many spaghetti and meatballs until they quit eating them.
So we started taking them off.
So we went from five in the cycle back to about one in the cycle again.
So from then on, I'd always say, now, wait a minute.
Let's don't get too much of this stuff.
Another funny thing is they'd say, I don't like spinach.
Take it off.
I said, well, I'd normally say, we're going to do what you want to do.
But I said, before you vote, you ought to know that spinach is pretty nutritious.
good for these different things.
And I said, probably your mother would want you to eat some spinach.
Yeah, that's right.
So I said, but we'll vote on it.
And I always vote to leave it on.
Compared to other institutions, were there any eating favorites here that were different from other places?
Did we eat more or less of something than
nationally was the norm?
I don't think so, except there are certain items when you go into the north that just didn't operate here.
There's sandwiches and certain items or casserole dishes they wouldn't eat here.
I know I tried to copy one from Michigan State.
That was a beautiful beef roll, I thought.
It was like a cinnamon roll, but it had beef rolled up in it, and you cooked this and put it, and you had gravy to go with it.
And it was so popular up there and here they wouldn't eat it at all.
And I had a friend that came down to Sam Houston from New York and thought he'd inject some sandwiches and smoothies we now have.
They wouldn't eat them.
And he was shocked to pieces.
Somewhere I remember in the 70s a group of student activists who wanted us to privatize the food service and called in a local, I mean a
a profit maker, and he started, I remember he said, now you tell me how many times a week you want this, this, this.
And then he added on, I think it was 7% or 8%.
One of the students said, what's that?
And he said, well, that's the profit.
We'll serve you whatever you want.
And the student said, whoa, whoa, whoa, no, we don't want to do that.
Well, that brings up a funny point.
You know, there's so much of the
community and even the faculty here at the time saw no reason why food service should make profit.
Because it was a service.
And I wish it worked that way, but it doesn't.
No, no.
They didn't understand what the... Let's see.
Proud moments.
Think back.
What are some of the, in your years of leadership, what are some of the things that make you the
now the most proud to have served those?
Oh, I think that you get an award for some group of students, like the battalion.
They condemn you one time, but then they award you another time, you know, for being outstanding.
Or the President's Association of Former Students does something.
I mean, they're the student council.
A lot of times, when you're being criticized for something, a lot of students will step up and do your defense and say, well, I stopped through.
And we've had that happen a lot of times.
And that's always a good feeling to have.
And then beyond that, when you get national awards of different kinds, we've got several of those.
So that always makes you feel better.
feel good, and it's not as good as having a student compliment, but it's good for the school.
But those little things come along, and they're mentioned specifically by groups occasionally that you serve.
So they don't come very often, and that was a difficult period during the hippie period of the school.
And we had less trouble in many schools, but we had some problems.
Were there ever any demonstrations that involved food service or in one of the dining halls?
Well, there was one.
Well, that was what President Rutter was doing.
It had to do with everybody had eaten on campus, as I recall, that was on campus.
There wasn't any place else, but he decided to be
mandatory board, I believe, back then one time.
They marched on his house and this, I'd had nothing to do with this.
And then he came along and to compromise he gave a five-day plan instead of seven-day plan.
We had 21 meals a week, what we started out with.
Now later on, I recommended we discontinued the compulsion board because
I told Howard Bestville, we don't really have a compulsion board.
I said, any student can go to the right people in the university and just get on.
I said, it's harassment to us.
Well, maybe I shouldn't have done that.
I don't know whether I had done it, if I had to do it or not.
But at the time, I was exasperated about it.
He said, fine.
Hard to sell the market with anything.
But he was very kind about it when he told you, no, it was not our issue.
He's just the ideal man to work for.
He and Mr. Cherry both, I enjoyed both of them tremendously.
I think one of the, let's see if you agree with me, I think one of our great blessings during the 60s and 70s is that we had continuity of leadership.
Yeah, oh yes, oh yes.
The...
It was like handing the baton to another member of the team.
That there was continuity when Mr. Rutter came ill and then died, and Williams, and the people reporting to them continued.
Yeah, there was no change down at my level, for example.
It just went right along.
How did the admission of women change food service, if any?
Well, quite a bit, but not immediately, because we didn't know what it was going to.
And I'll give you a good example of that.
When I renovated Sebiza in 76, we still didn't have many women.
We had some, but desserts were popular.
It seemed everybody was eating two or three.
And we had a large section just for desserts, and many desserts.
And that's over the, it began to drop.
And hardly anyone was eating a salad.
We could put out salads.
And maybe there wouldn't be 5% of the boys eat salads.
Now that's totally reversed.
Completely reversed.
And of course the girls like more dainty varieties of things.
This is like it is in the home.
But it took us a while to get geared for that.
One reason was they had so few girls, you couldn't gear to that, because that didn't suit the boys.
But the setup like it is is pretty good, where you have a good mixture.
And I always wanted to experiment with where I served only women.
See, I never did get to do that.
Let's see.
By the power vested in me by asking this question, let's go back and you could change anything and redo anything during those 20 years plus.
Is there any change you would make since you now are blessed with hindsight?
Well, I don't know.
It's pretty hard to say because, well, of course, I'd like to come in with the ability to make my own decisions, to spend my own money and salaries to hire.
Better salaries, okay.
That would up things a great deal in my opinion.
One of the things I'd have done if I'd had my saying was to not

go to our own people in our facilities construction for advice and help by going to the outside, the people I knew because I had to pay an extra person I thought and I knew enough to work with those people and some people I'm sure didn't want to do that but I did and then I would have built some things a little faster than we did
But beyond that, I had such good support.
It was just amazing.
Right now, the complications of the design and location of the kitchen on the faculty club.
Oh, that was a, that, that, that, yes, that was, that was one that.
Any others?
No, the faculty club and the MSC were the two that was really a thorn in our side.
The others, the others were,
You see, the buildings were there, and we had to build within what we could, and everybody wanted to do what was the best.
It was a question of what was the best.
That was the tough part.
How do you do this thing with a structure like Sebiza or Duncan?
And that's the reason I really fumbled with that thing, and I guess that's the word for it, for 10 years on Sebiza.
We've made enough plans to fill half this room, probably, trying to figure out what do you do.
And of course, they're renovating again today.
It's very, very nice.
Very nice operation, I think.
But the times have changed a little bit.
I think they have less volume there.
They can do some things that are attractive.
Any advice you would give to today's A&M leaders
about food service?

Well, to give it good support would be one thing, and to never get tricked on what I think is a trick is to go to this commercializing, which they call privatization, which is nothing more than commercial profitization.
And I realize there are some places and some times when if you can't get competent people to help,
that people have to do that, but they do rake off a pretty good profit, and if you can avoid that, why do it?
As far as you're aware, about what is that profit margin at other universities that have privatized?
Oh, I think it's only, well, maybe, it ranges everywhere from two to five percent, but that's a lot of money.
That's a lot of money.
Here, they'd do it for one percent.
I believe
that in order for us to commercially outfit to get the hooks in Texas A&M, they wouldn't hesitate to pay a million dollars just for the right to have one contract.
Well, and I found being the CEO at two different campuses, one of the difficulties of dealing with the commercial firm is that I couldn't get their attention
until it was time to renew the contract.
Well, that's one problem they have with some of the companies.
The companies vary a good little bit.
I have the experience of working with some of those people after I retired here.
And I helped them in the sense that I would help them work out some problems, but I got familiar with their personnel.
And they have fine people.
I have no complaint about them.

ethics and morals of their individuals but the company policy and and necessity to make a good profit is there and if you have to cut corners to make that profit then most of them will cut those corners very few would sacrifice the company in order to save a and m food circuits let's see a while ago you mentioning cervix to the board

recall if you can were there any special uh favorite foods of uh regents that uh y'all would uh need to keep in mind when there was a board meeting no not really that was a strange thing i had heard of some prior to my time but we never had a problem as a matter of fact they were an easy group to get along with and an easy group to please
One funny incident I had with Mr. Weisenbacher, who was very opinionated, of course.
He used to go out and jog or walk, and he'd come in early, and he'd go back in the kitchen and talk to these people.
And I told somebody I wasn't afraid of Mr. Weisenbacher talking.
I was afraid of my people answering.
But as a result of that, he just became a closer friend of the whole operation, including the individual thing.
So we enjoyed it.
All right, so you don't remember any special desserts that needed to be made because certain regions liked this or that specialty?
I don't believe there was a single one.
They seemed to like most of them.
We'd normally have a pretty good variety, and sometimes one might ask if we had some.
